 Arguing that consumption is myopic and depends on the perception of status
 in a near-term while savings are cumulative in an intertemporal model for
 consumer choice, we let the representative consumer in the model optimise
 utility inclusive of status.
 As the signalling utility a consumer receives from consumption must come
 from either high-priced non-durable consumption or long-term durable consumptio
n, the signaling is viewed as the utility obtained from consumption of quality
 and owned assets over time.
 Taking an approach different from the PIH, therefore we thus consider how
 types of non-monetary wealth may matter towards the perception of risk
 (monetary or non-monetary) and attempt to relate the substitution between
 saving for assets and consumption of quality in the life-time of the consumer
