 Therefore, the consumer evaluates the lottery 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(A_{t}-\delta\psi+\sigma(\psi),p),(A_{t}-\delta\psi,1-p)\}$
\end_inset

.
 Using a weighting function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(p)=\frac{p^{\alpha}}{p^{\alpha}+(1-p)^{\alpha}}$
\end_inset

 and a value function 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon(A)$
\end_inset

, the utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u(\psi)$
\end_inset

 which the consumer optimises is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
u(\psi) & =\sum w(p)\upsilon(A_{t+1})
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's assume a reference points 
\begin_inset Formula $A'$
\end_inset

, the lottery's value would be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
u(\psi) & =\frac{p^{\alpha}}{p^{\alpha}+(1-p)^{\alpha}}\upsilon(A_{t}-\delta\psi+\sigma(\psi)-A')+\frac{(1-p)^{\alpha}}{p^{\alpha}+(1-p)^{\alpha}}\upsilon(A_{t}-\delta\psi-A')
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now arrive at the specifics form of the utlility function by choosing
 the forms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\psi)$
\end_inset

, the value function 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon(A)$
\end_inset

 and the references points.
 We can for example use 
\begin_inset Formula $A'=\frac{A_{1}+A_{2}}{2}$
\end_inset

 and the PT value function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat*}{1}
\upsilon(\Delta) & =\begin{cases}
\Delta^{\gamma} & \Delta\ge0\\
-\lambda(-\Delta)^{\gamma} & \Delta<0
\end{cases}
\end{alignat*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What's interesting is that if we have high-risk activities - utilities from
